			<h1>Icons and images</h1>
			<div class="breakout">
			The MyService iconography style aligns with the Department of Veteran's Affairs personality and echoes other Australian Government service brands. Icons are in the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flat_design" target="_blank" rel="external">flat design style</a>, meaning they use minimal stylistic elements.
			</div>
			
			<h2>Icon features</h2>
			
			<div class="row">
				<div class="col-xs-4">
					<h4 class="heading-underline">Consistent line wieght</h4>
					<img class="sg-icon-example" src="../../../docs/images/styleguide/sg-ico-line-weight.svg" alt="Icon example of consistent line weight">
				</div>
				<div class="col-xs-4">
					<h4 class="heading-underline">Geometric shapes</h4>
					<img class="sg-icon-example" src="../../../docs/images/styleguide/sg-ico-geometric.svg" alt="Icon example of gemoetric shapes">
				</div>
				<div class="col-xs-4">
					<h4 class="heading-underline">Rounded corners</h4>
					<img class="sg-icon-example" src="../../../docs/images/styleguide/sg-ico-rounded.svg" alt="Icon example of rounded corners">
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<hr>
			
			<h2>Icons in headings</h2>

			<p>Icons used alongside text in a heading can help convey a key message. For example, a green tick icon in a heading that reads 'You have submitted your claim' will assist the user in understanding they have just completed a process. Headings, <font color="red">&#60;h1&#62;</font> and <font color="red">&#60;h2&#62;</font>, are available for use with icons.</p></p>
			
			<div class="example-box">
				<h6>EXAMPLE</h6>
				<table class="table">
					<tbody>
						<tr><td><h2><img src="../../../docs/images/ico-tick-green.svg" alt="Success tick icon"> Submitted</h2></td></tr>
						<tr><td class="example-code">
							<code>&lt;h2&gt;&lt;img src="ico-tick-green.svg" alt="Success tick icon"&gt; Submitted&lt;/h2&gt;</code>
						</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
			
